November 8, 1997<br><br>
Vietnam Appeals for Aid After Storm<br><br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
A.P. INDEXES: TOP STORIES | NEWS | SPORTS | BUSINESS | TECHNOLOGY | ENTERTAINMENT <br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br><br>
Filed at 7:37 a.m. EST<br><br>
By The Associated Press<br>
HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Vietnam made a rare appeal for international aid today in the aftermath of a typhoon that wiped out coastal villages and left thousands of families homeless. <br><br>
At least 300 people were killed when Typhoon Linda lashed southern Vietnam on Sunday and Monday, catching several provinces off guard. About 2,000 people are still missing -- at least 800 of them lost at sea. <br><br>
``We have exerted our maximum effort in our rescue effort, but our government has also delivered an official call for international assistance,'' Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Pham Thuy Thanh told reporters. <br><br>
Vietnam's southern provinces need at least $12 million in immediate relief assistance for basic necessities, U.N. disaster workers said. <br><br>
France and South Korea have both offered about $100,000, while Switzerland earlier this week donated $400,000. <br><br>
In all, the storm caused about $200 million in damage to Ca Mau and Kien Giang provinces, Vietnam's Central Committee for Flood and Storm Control said. Schools and most medical clinics were destroyed in the area. <br><br>
The region's lack of preparation increased the damage and casualties, said Marshal Silver, director of the U.N. disaster unit. <br><br>
``We're talking about one of the most populous areas in Vietnam,'' he said. ``This is not an area prone to disasters and it caught the fishing boats without any warning.'' <br><br>

